# Security Guidelines

## Credentials & Secrets
- NEVER log, commit, expose, or console.log API keys, tokens, or user credentials
- Store secrets in `.env.local` (git-ignored); prefix with `VITE_` for Vite access
- Example: `VITE_POSTHOG_API_KEY` — loaded by `chrome-extension/vite.config.mts`
- LLM API keys live in `chrome.storage` via `packages/storage/` — never in source

## Chrome Extension Permissions
- Request minimal permissions in `manifest.json` — principle of least privilege
- `chrome.debugger` attaches to tabs on demand; always detach in `onDetach` listener
- Never open raw CDP port 9222; always use `chrome.debugger` API

## Content Security Policy
- Never use `eval()` or `new Function()` — violates MV3 CSP and is blocked
- Never use `innerHTML` with user-controlled or page-sourced content — use textContent or sanitize first
- DOM injection via content scripts must sanitize before rendering

## Input Validation
- Validate and sanitize all user-provided URLs before navigating — check protocol, reject `javascript:` and `data:` schemes
- Validate LLM responses before using them to drive browser actions
- Sanitize content extracted from web pages before storing or displaying

## Error Handling
- Never surface raw error objects to the UI — they may contain sensitive path or key information
- Use structured error messages: `logger.error('context: message', { safeData })` not `logger.error(error)`

## Data Privacy
- Avoid logging page content, form values, or screenshot data to persistent storage
- PostHog analytics: only send anonymized event names, never PII or page content
